U.S. stocks declined, sending the
Standard & Poorâ€™s 500 Index to a second straight drop, after S&P
cut debt ratings for Portugal and Greece and a Bank of America
Corp. downgrade drove down semiconductor companies.  Chipmakers in the  S&P 500  lost 0.9 percent, the most among
24 groups, after Bank of America said the Japanese earthquake on
March 11 may disrupt supplies. Intel Corp. fell 1.2 percent to
lead losses in the  Dow Jones Industrial Average . General
Electric Co. fell 1.1 percent after agreeing to a $3.2 billion
takeover.  The S&P 500 decreased 0.2 percent to 1,307.39 at 9:38 a.m.
in New York. The Dow slipped 4.08 points, or less than 0.1
percent, to 12,193.80.  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
